			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(center)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> <date>June 18<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. Sivan 21<hi rend="sup">st</hi>. 5595</date></p>
				<p>Dear Uncle.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Last Evening <persName>Mr Goldsmidt</persName> gave me your letter of the<lb/> day before while at <persName>Mr. Solis&#39;</persName> to marry <persName>Israel<add>&#63;</add> Levy</persName> of <placeName>Richmond</placeName> to<lb/> <persName>Mr S.&#39;s</persName> daughter.  I am really glad to understand that you are<lb/> so much better and only hope it may long continue to be the<lb/> same.  You want the news of this place<lb/> but as I am engaged as you well know from early in the morning to late in the evening<lb/> I do hear but little.  But some few Items I will just tell.  Yester&#45;<lb/>day week <persName>Miss Israel</persName> was married&#59; the wedding went off delightfully<lb/> people danced&#44; sang &#38; were merry.  Some remained till three or four in<lb/> the morning&#44; and I staid till near &#189; past eleven.  The same may be<lb/> said of yesterday&#39;s <sic>frolick</sic>&#59; there was almost literally &#8220;fife&#44; fiddle &#38;<lb/> drum&#44;&#8221; or tambourine&#44; fiddles &#38; <sic>clarionett</sic>&#44; I left also about &#189; aft. 11<lb/> and already I am up a little after 5 to send this if possible by<lb/> <persName>David I. Cohen</persName> whom I just stumbled upon in the street yester&#45;<lb/>day morning during a recess which I gave to the boys&#44; in consequence of<lb/> keeping them in till 2 on account of the wedding.  <persName>Mr. Allen</persName><lb/> made a Berit<add>&#63;</add> last <date>Thursday</date>&#44; which is the fourth we have<lb/> had in about three weeks.  This year thus far there have been 10<lb/> funerals&#44; 9 Berits and three weddings&#44; besides several female children<lb/> were born during this same periods.  <persName>Miss Rose Hays</persName> is to be<lb/> married this fall to <persName>Mr. Charles Marx</persName> of <placeName>Richmond</placeName>&#44; but this<lb/> no doubt is old news.  <persName>Mr. Mordecai</persName> was here during the<lb/> holydays&#44; when I delivered an address on education&#44; I have not<lb/> yet received it back&#59; I believe that it was not very well<lb/> received by many on account of its coming home too much&#59; but<lb/> this of course cannot be avoided&#44; when one wishes to do his duty.<lb/>  <persName>Mr. Mordecai</persName> came here for the purpose of leaving <persName>Laura</persName> at<lb/> a boarding school&#59; she appears to be a very fine girl.  I understand<lb/> that <persName>Miss Peixotto</persName> is learning the stock making business&#59; I believe<lb/> it must be true&#44; altho&#39; she did not tell me so herself.  My <sic>scholl</sic> now<lb/> numbers 16 boys&#59; <persName>David Sarfaty</persName> has not yet come&#44; and I doubt whether<lb/> he will come in a hurry.  <persName>Simha P.</persName> told me that she had heard but not direct</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>from her uncle <persName>Peixotto</persName> that <persName>Mr. Sarfaty</persName> did not approve of my circular&#59;<lb/> <persName>Mr. S.</persName> by the way is a very intelligent man&#44; but rather too fond of setting<lb/> himself up as a literary judge and <sic>critick</sic>&#44; and in this way he has <sic>criticised</sic><lb/> some of my sermons which I allowed <persName>Simha</persName> to copy and send to him&#44;<lb/> which however to me appears rather ridiculous as his education<lb/> has been by no means one from which a man could derive that<lb/> peculiar talent so requisite to form a correct judgment of literary com&#45;<lb/>positions&#44; which is full as difficult as book&#45;keeping or buying &#38; selling<lb/> dry goods and groceries.  Several people have spoken about sending their<lb/> children but I know not whether they are coming or not.  <persName>Miss Rebecca<lb/> Phillips</persName> desired me to convey to you her regrets at not having seen you.<lb/>  She sends her love&#44; as do also many others.  <persName>Theodore</persName> wrote to me and he<lb/> &#38; <persName>Myrtilla</persName> both desire their affectionate remembrance.  <persName>Isaac Seixas</persName><lb/> inquires about you all in a letter I got on <date>Monday</date>.  <persName>Mr. Goldsmit</persName><lb/> &#38; <persName>Mr Hyneman</persName> were much gratified by your hospitality.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Give my love to aunt and all the rest.  Not having any more time<lb/> they must excuse me for being brief.</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">Your affectionate nephew</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Isaac Leeser</persName>.</p>
